  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Build a school for 215 pupils in southern Zambia</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Kamawindow, which means a &apos;small window&apos; is a community school in Choma District of Zambia that enrolls 215 pupils in a dilapidated and unsafe one classroom block. Established as a community school in 2012 in Mandona village, pupils at Kamawindow still learn in a makeshift building made from mud and poles while sitting on wooden poles as there are no desks. The thatched structure with visible cracks (Kamawindow) is a glaring danger to both the pupils and teachers.</narrative>
  </description>
